    • looseEquals

      public static <V extends Vector<V>> boolean looseEquals(@Nonnull V v1, @Nonnull V v2)
      Checks for loose equality between the provided values v1 and v2. This accounts for potential floating point imprecision by accepting a small margin of error defined by Scalars.EPSILON. Although geometrically accurate in Euclidean space, this is more computationally expensive compared to fastEquals(Vector, Vector).
      Type Parameters:
      V - The type of vector to compare
      Parameters:
      v1 - The first value to compare
      v2 - The second value to compare
      Returns:
      true if the squared Euclidean distance between the two vectors is less than Scalars.EPSILON raised to the power of 2
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - When the vector is a variable size vector, and the dimensions (the number of scalar components) of the two vectors are different
      See Also:
      • fastEquals(Vector, Vector)

    • fastEquals

      public static <V extends Vector<V>> boolean fastEquals(@Nonnull V v1, @Nonnull V v2)
      Checks for loose equality between the provided values v1 and v2. This account for potential floating point imprecision by accepting a small margin of error defined by Scalars.EPSILON. Unlike looseEquals(Vector, Vector), this uses the Manhattan distance between the two vectors, and may lead to unexpected behavior.
      Type Parameters:
      V - The type of vector to compare
      Parameters:
      v1 - The first value to compare
      v2 - The second value to compare
      Returns:
      true if the Manhattan distance between the two vectors is less than Scalars.EPSILON
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - When the vector is a variable size vector, and the dimensions (the number of scalar components) of the two vectors are different
      See Also:
      • looseEquals(Vector, Vector)
